name: AMBSubn_Shepherd.Barking.Neighborhood cottage.Road noise.Processed_EM.wav
description: Sound recording of the distant barking of a german shepherd. This is the post-processing version. Compare with the original without processing here https://freesound.org/people/newlocknew/sounds/677657/ One example of the creativity in post-processing field recordings, and the possible increase in quality if you have a inexpensive recorder. Naturally, this example is not a panacea for all cases, but only shows what can be done if it makes sense to compete for quality. Of course, the fact that it takes a lot of time can be important. But it can be a lot of fun if you like to experiment. So, the recording of the barking of a German shepherd in the neighboring area, more precisely in the area following the neighboring area. The recording also features the recorder's own noise and fairly stable distant highway noise (which always seems closer and louder on the recording), which contributes to normal noise removal, with no significant audible artifacts. Task: to reduce the own noise of the recording and attenuate the noise of the track, to zoom in a bit and expand the barking of the shepherd dog (stereo image), while the noise of the track should not be expanded in the panorama. The following explanations assume that the reader has some experience with sound editors, and in particular with spectral noise reduction and noise reduction settings. It should be added that in this case only equalizers or filters with a linear phase response can be used. Stages: 1. First pass of noise editing. We train the denoiser and when rendering we get only the output noise by clicking the corresponding checkbox. Now this noise is subtracted from the original recording, flipping it (noise) in phase. We get partial removal of noise from the record. That's not all. 2. We also copy the output noise obtained in step 1 into a separate file (we create a new empty file in the editor) for its separate processing and subsequent addition to the original. 3. Back to the main file again. Second pass of noise editing. We train the denoiser and when rendering we get only the output noise by clicking the corresponding checkbox. Now this noise is subtracted from the original recording, flipping it (noise) in phase. We get an almost complete removal of noise (intrinsic noise and trace noise) from the recording. 4. Now you can expand the dog barking in the main file. I'm expanding my stereo with a multi-band exciter with mid/side capability. I usually expand in the frequency range of 200-1000 Hz in the side channel. Of course, this corridor may vary slightly, depending on the material. It turns out very well. With mid-side EQs, the same effect cannot be achieved. I also highlight the fundamental frequencies of the bark with the equalizer a little, so that there is more “weight”. 5. In the output noise saved in a separate file, which we obtained in step 1, we first make a correction with an equalizer. Since we actually have highway noise here, which has a frequency response rolloff of about 1500 Hz, we adjust the EQ shelving filter with a smooth roll-off at high frequencies of 18-24 dB / octave to attenuate the noise that lies above the actual highway noise. Those. we attenuate the noise of the recording. Here it is important not to overdo it, and not to make the sound too sterile at high frequencies. In my case, attenuation of 6.5 dB was enough. 6. Next, in the output noise “corrected” in the previous paragraph, saved in a separate file, we reduce the volume level if there is a subjective desire to reduce it and accentuate other elements in the end due to this. This has to be done by finding a balance, experimentally. 7. Finally, the "corrected" output noise is copied and added to the main audio file, in which we have already done two passes of noise reduction and extended the barking of the dog. This is all. Here's a way. Seems to be pretty detailed. I hope someone will be useful. Of course, we can say that it is better to use better equipment, which greatly simplifies life. And it's hard to disagree with that. Field recording made in Russia, near the city of Ekaterinburg. Recorded September 22, 2022 on Tascam DR-05x, with post editing.
